Introduction

The this report aims to present an ARIMA model trained to predict the flow of the River. The training data is loaded directly from the R package datasets and involves measurements of the annual flow of the River Nile at Aswan between 1871 and 1970 in 10^8 m^3. Visualization on the R package of the time series, autocorrelation function, and partial autocorrelation function are used for the diagnosis of the stationary of the data. The R package forecast is used to estimate the parameters of the model.

For practicality, I load the data in the variable nile, and then I graph the time series, the acf, pacf reports that are the start point of the analysis.

nile=Nile
par(mfrow=c(3,1))
ts.plot(nile)
acf(nile, lag.max = 30)
pacf(nile, lag.max = 30)

Fig. 1 Nile river time series, acf and pacf

The acf decays quickly and this behavior is an insight of an AR(1) model, there is also a big spike at lag one in the pacf, which confirms AR(1) model. However, differences of levels over the years make me think that the model could require a differentiation.

nile.diff = diff(nile)
par(mfrow=c(3,1))
ts.plot(nile.diff)
acf(nile.diff, lag.max = 100)
pacf(nile.diff)

Fig. 2

The first spike of the acf tells me there is an MA(1) in the series. One big spike in the pacf means there is an ar(1), although the second spike is very small, I am going to evaluate its inclusion as an AR(2) component.

fit = arima(nile.diff, order = c(1,0,1))
tsdiag(fit)

Fig. 4

This graph of the differenced data is telling me that an ARIMA(1,1,1) will be a good fit as all the p values are over 0.05. I am going to study the data-set using the function auto.arima from the forecast package,

After a look at the residuals, acf and the p values for Ljung-Box statistic, I see that the four models are a good fit. Now I will do a further analysis using the aic of the models and the standard errors of the coefficients.

From this R output, I see that the best aic is for the model ARIMA(1,1,1) and it is worth it an increment of the complexity from the model ARMA(1,1) adding a difference d=1. The model ARIMA(2,1,1) whilst is more complex doesnt increase the aic of the model, on the other hand, the low value of 0.59 for its coefficient standard error ratio coincides with the quite small second spike of the pacf of the figure x which made me consider an AR(2) component at the beginning of the analysis, but which now I am rejecting. Although the model ARIMA(0,1,1) is offered by the auto.arima function passes the Ljung-Box statistic, it doesnt have a good aic coefficient compared with the other models.

The ARIMA(1,1,1) model has AR parameter \(\phi_1=2.130484\), and MA parameter \(\theta_1=14.452883\), and the white noise variance \(var(Z_t) = \sigma_z^2=1\). And the model is \[(1-\phi_1B)(1-B)X_t=(1-\theta_1B)Z_t\] \[(1-2.130484 B)(1-B)X_t=(1-14.452883 B)Z_t\]

Conclusions

An ARIMA model has been presented, The model consists of two learned parameters, the auto-regressive (\(\phi\)), the Moving average (\(\theta\)), and a regular difference. No evidence of seasonality was learned from the figures as the information provided was by year. The autocorrelation function and the partial autocorrelation function were used to identify and verify the assumptions of the model, however, I also used the relation coefficient standard error and Akaike Information Criterion.
